81–1431","1380–1429":"1380–1429","1421–1487":"1421–1487","–1431":"–1431","1323–1395":"1323–1395","1352–1419":"1352–1419","about 1381":"circa 1381","8 May 1419":"8 mei 1419","31 May 1421":"31 mei 1421","1352":"1352","1395":"1395","1382":"1382","1381":"1381","1380":"1380","1323":"1323","1487":"1487","1421":"1421","about 1369":"circa 1369","1431":"1431","1376":"1376","25 April 1431":"25 april 1431","1419":"1419","1429":"1429","after 1431":"1431","1406":"1406","Sockburn, Durham, England":"Sockburn, Durham, England","Durham, England":"Durham, England","New Malton, Yorkshire, England":"New Malton, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"about 1381–25 April 1431":"about 1381–25 April 1431","1376–Male":"1376–Deceased","1381–1431":"1381–1431","1380–1429":"1380–1429","1421–1487":"1421–1487","–1431":"–1431","1323–1395":"1323–1395","1352–1419":"1352–1419","about 1381":"about 1381","8 May 1419":"8 May 1419","31 May 1421":"31 May 1421","1352":"1352","1395":"1395","1382":"1382","1381":"1381","1380":"1380","1323":"1323","1487":"1487","1421":"1421","about 1369":"about 1369","1431":"1431","1376":"1376","25 April 1431":"25 April 1431","1419":"1419","1429":"1429","after 1431":"1431","1406":"1406","Sockburn, Durham, England":"Sockburn, Durham, England","Durham, England":"Durham, England","New Malton, Yorkshire, England":"New Malton, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Conyers","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Yorkshire, of Norman origin): habitational name from either of two places in northern France, Coignières in Seine-et-Oise or Cogners in Sarthe. Alternatively, a variant of   Conyer  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Conyer","meanings":["English: occupational name for a minter, a coiner of money, from an agent derivative of Old French <i>coignier</i> ‘to stamp money, to mint’."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":1,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Conyers was born about 1381, in Sockburn, Durham, England, his father, John Conyers, was 11379 and his mother, Lady Elizabeth de Aton, was 31. He had at least 1 son and 6 daughters with Elizabeth Pert. He died on 25 April 1431, in Durham, England, at the age of 51."},"et":{"about 1381–25 April 1431":"umbes 1381–25. aprill 1431","1376–Male":"1376–Surnud","1381–1431":"1381–1431","1380–1429":"1380–1429","1421–1487":"1421–1487","–1431":"–1431","1323–1395":"1323–1395","1352–1419":"1352–1419","about 1381":"umbes 1381","8 May 1419":"8. mai 1419","31 May 1421":"31. mai 1421"